## Plan gate (attempt 2) — Tier 1 four-seat: BLOCK (3 GO / 1 BLOCK)
- Claude Opus: GO (empirically validated); Gemini Pro: GO; pi/pilms: GO; GPT-5.5 xhigh (codex): BLOCK — two subtle valid catches:
  1. Full 40/64-hex validateSHA is NOT sufficient: in a SHA-1 repo a 64-hex string (or in SHA-256 a 40-hex string) can be a BRANCH NAME that rev-parse resolves to a moving tip; capturing the resolved OID merely freezes that unsafe resolution. REQUIRED: require resolvedOID == inputSHA (input must BE the commit OID, not just resolve to one) + a regression test for a hex-looking ref of the other width.
  2. Cleanup ordering remove->prune->RemoveAll can leave stale .git/worktrees metadata if 'worktree remove' fails but the filesystem delete succeeds. REQUIRED: prune AFTER RemoveAll.

## PLAN AMENDMENT (incorporated for gate attempt 3)
1. After 'git rev-parse --verify <sha>^{commit}' -> resolvedOID, REQUIRE resolvedOID == inputSHA (both lowercase full hex; rev-parse emits lowercase). If they differ, the input resolved to something other than itself (a hex-looking branch/tag/mismatched-width ref) -> reject with ErrInvalidSHA. This guarantees the input IS the recorded commit OID, immune to hex-looking moving refs in either object format. (Legitimate recorded git_sha is a direct commit OID, so equality always holds.)
2. Cleanup ordering: 'git worktree remove --force <dir>' -> os.RemoveAll(dir) -> 'git worktree prune' (prune runs LAST so it reaps any admin entry left when remove failed but the dir was deleted). Idempotent + no-leak preserved.
3. Tests add: a branch named with 64-hex chars in a SHA-1 repo (and/or a tag whose name/oid is hex) -> ErrInvalidSHA via the resolvedOID==input guard (proves no moving-ref/peeled-tag checkout); a cleanup case where 'remove' is forced to fail but RemoveAll+prune still leaves no stale .git/worktrees entry.
